Saturday, March 9, 1946

Put the finishing touch on the reproduction section this morning and took it over to the zoo this noon to be copied.

Spent 3 hours at the zoo at a meeting of the board at noon. In the evening started on the hunting [rattles]] section.

Heifetz concert this evening.

Notes:

Karen

Not sure about "hunting" rattles. Also, I write rattles separated from Heifetz by 2 or 3 returns, but they keep merging on the transcript.

Sunday, March 10, 1946

Spent the day working on the hunting section. Made good progress.

Shorty brought in a small gopher from Lake Hodges.

Shaw took my car out to Santee
1 gopher S. COR Fletcher Hills
2 garters LOR Fletcher Hills
1 garter DOR Fletcher Hills
1 HT Fletcher Hills
1 Alligator lizard DOR Fletcher Hills
1 HT alive Suncrest

Notes:

Karen

Not sure what S.COR is, but I think LOR is Live On Arrival, and DOR is Dead on Arrival (?)

Sunday, April 21, 1946

This morning I picked up Chickering at Glendale at 8:35. We then drove to the desert via San Gorgonio Pass.
Had car trouble, presumably vapor lock at Rialto and lost time. Also much missing and stalling all through San Gorgonio Pass.

1 Gopher L DOR Fingal, Riverside County Grass- light brush. Seems pure annectens

Passed up many DORs between Whitewater adn Palm Springs and from there south as we were afraid to stop the car. Did stop at Palm Springs to see Dr. Cockerell And couldn't start again without help from a mechanic. A long and painful delay in the heat. Stopped at Bensons at 3:40 and reached Crickeners in the Borrego Valley at 4:30. Then drove up to Palm Canyon and back.

Started an evening drive from Crickeners at 7:30. Clear and fairly warm with little wind.
(Continued on April 23rd)

references.

Sunday, August 11, 1946

Worked all day on Indian
snake-bite remedies and made
good progress. Not easy to
coordinate and arrange. This
Indian - rattler section is
going to be much longer than
orginially contemplated.
From 11 to 12 at the zoo I
talked to Prof. Zimmerman, who,
with Clifford Pope has worked
not fundamental theories of
rattler furmatch. No dunst they
are right and have proved me
wrong on several counts, but
there are still some seniors
gaps in their theory from a
purely mechanical standpoint

Saturday, August 17, 1946

Worked all day and evening on
Indians and Rattlers and made good
progress. This section should be finished
shortly
______________________________________________________________
It's been a tough week -- one
of the most difficult I can remember. I
suppose nowhere is age more evident
than in the loss of ability ot withstand
nervous shocks -- such as that involved
in the death of a 15 year-old dog. The
terrible homesickness that no home can
assuage; the lonliness that is always
present; the all-gone feeling in the
pit of the stomach; under these circumstances
it is hard to be objective and retain
a fair sense of relative values. Only a
little dog -- yes -- but a tearing bitter loss
just the same. No patter down the hall;
the scratch on the door that never comes.

Page Edit History:
  • comicsenchantress 01/25/2013 05:22 PM
  • BPOC 05/10/2012 12:51 PM

Sunday, August 18, 1946

Worked all day, except for
visitors, on the Indian section of
the rattle book and finished the first
draft.
Chap. Grant and Billy Woodin were
here for about 2 hours in the morning
to discuss herpetological record
systems.
Kent Christenson a budding young
herpetologist from Utah - but now in the
marines - called tonight.

must be done. I am thinking of
tackling the Food section next.

the gopher snake paper -- Western U.S.
This is the last unprinted ms. ; for all
the time since its completion has been
spent on the Rattler life History book.

long time.

Saturday, December 28, 1946

Drove to Whittier this morning and in the afternoon went to the meeting of the Western Society of Naturalists. Conducted the business meeting.

In the evening gave the Presedential talk on Rattlesnakes. Their Habits and life Histories, dwelling mostly on the material collected in teh letter questionnaire. Talked for one hour and 20 minutes.
